### Ascension Island and Tristan da Cunha

[Ascension Island](/Ascension_Island), a volcanic island with a stark, almost lunar landscape, hosts a population of around eight hundred individuals. The majority of these are Saint Helenians, who primarily reside in [Georgetown](/Georgetown,_Ascension_Island), situated on the island's west coast. A smaller settlement, [Two Boats](/Two_Boats,_Ascension_Island), is located inland.

[Tristan da Cunha](/Tristan_da_Cunha), often cited as the most remote inhabited archipelago on Earth, has a population of approximately three hundred people. They are concentrated in the single settlement of [Edinburgh of the Seven Seas](/Edinburgh_of_the_Seven_Seas), nestled on the island's north coast.

### Nationality

The inhabitants of [Saint Helena, Ascension and Tristan da Cunha](/Saint_Helena,_Ascension_and_Tristan_da_Cunha) hold [British Overseas Territories citizenship](/British_Overseas_Territories_citizen). A significant legislative change occurred on 21 May 2002, when the [British Overseas Territories Act 2002](/British_Overseas_Territories_Act_2002) granted them full [British citizenship](/British_citizenship). This development was met with considerable relief and a sense of renewed connection to the wider world. As a result, a distinct [Saint Helena passport](/Saint_Helena_passport) is issued to these citizens.

